EIS 28[bold]Written evidence submitted by the CBI Minerals Group[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]i
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]CBI
[normal] Minerals Group represents the minerals extraction industry within the United Kingdom including all major non-energy minerals and coal. The Group represents 
[normal]over 
[normal]500 mineral extraction and related companies either directly through being members of the Grou
[normal]p or indirectly through member trade associations. 
[normal]ii
[normal]              
[normal]The approximate total value of minerals produced in the UK (including oil and gas) was £37.7 billion in 2011.
[normal] The industry (excluding oil and gas) usually 
[normal]extracts between 22
[normal]0 
[normal]and 350 
[normal]million tonnes of minerals 
[normal]per annum from the UK landmass, 
[normal]directly contributes over £10
[normal] billion a year to the economy and provides
[normal] direct and indirect employment
[normal] around 8
[normal]0
[normal],000 people. It
[normal] is essential to provide the raw materials on which many important in
[normal]dustries depend. Minerals are the largest material flow in the Country.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Iii
[normal]              
[normal]The purpose of this evidence is to highlight the important role of the UK based minerals extraction industry plays in supporting 
[normal]sustainable economic growth
[normal] and that s
[normal]ustainable d
[normal]evelopment is only achievable by ensuring an adequate and steady supply of all minerals
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Executive Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Questions[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]contribution
[normal] that the 
[normal]indigenous minerals industry makes
[normal] to the economy is highlighted in paragraph 142 of the National Planning Policy framework published by the Government in March 2012. This states:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]142. Minerals are essential to support sustainable 
[normal]economic growth and our quality of life. It is therefore important that there is a sufficient supply of material to provide the infrastructure, buildings, energy and goods that the country needs. However, since minerals are a finite natural resource, and c
[normal]an only be worked where they are found, it is important to make best use of them to secure their long-term conservation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/6077/2116950.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]              
[normal]This importance is restated in 
[normal]the 
[normal]Resource Security Action Plan
[normal] published by the Government in March 2012. This states in paragraph 21:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]21. It is essenti
[normal]al that there is an adequate and steady supply of minerals to provide the raw materials for infrastructure, buildings and goods that society, industry and the economy need. Government recognises that where there is increasing and unprecedented demand for n
[normal]ew mineral resources, such as the ‘speciality’ metals vital for a range of high-tech applications and green technologies, further primary production will be necessary as there is insufficient recyclate from end-of-life products to meet new demand.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/resource-security-action-plan-making-the-most-of-valuable-materials
[normal]&#xa0;
