[normal]              
[normal]The national and regional 
[normal]co
[normal]ntribution
[normal] of the sector is more clearly demonstrated by looking at case studies:
[normal]Case Study 1: 
[normal]Cleveland Potash
[normal] Boulby Potash Mine
[normal] 
[normal]Cleveland Potash owns and oper
[normal]ates a potash mine (Boulby Mine
[normal])
[normal] on the n
[normal]orth east coast of Yorkshire.  The C
[normal]ompany 
[normal]produces
[normal] in the order of 3
[normal] million tonnes per annum (
[normal]mtpa
[normal]) 
[normal]of 
[normal]potash ore and refines 
[normal]this into 1mtpa 
[normal]of 
[normal]potash mainly used in the fertiliser industry. Although the Company produces enough potash to satisfy the UK demand, in practice they supply about half 
[normal]of 
[normal]this 
[normal]market with the remainder being imported from Germany, Russia and Canada.  In order to access the potash ore deposit, the Company also mines rock salt
[normal], which occurs in association with potash,
[normal] producing about 
[normal]0.8 m
[normal]tpa which is mostly sold to local authorit
[normal]ies and highway authorities as de-icing salt. 
[normal]The Company contributes £225M per year of economic activity as measured by product sales.  They support many local small suppliers and service companies.  Half their sales are overseas with approximate foreign
[normal] earnings of £100M per year.
[normal]The Company employs approximately 900 persons in high quality jobs, and a further 150 full time contractor employees. All direct employees are employed at the Boulby Mine with a few
[normal] based at
[normal] the nearby export terminal on the Ri
[normal]ver Tees. A socio-
[normal]economic study carried out on behalf of the company concluded that they support approximately 4,000 up-stream and down-stream jobs with a predominantly regional impact.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Case Study 2: 
[normal]Kier Minerals Ltd Greenburn Surface Coal Mine
[normal]Kier Minerals Ltd (part of Kier Group Plc)   currently own and operate a surface coal mine in the UK, the Greenburn Surface Mine, near New Cumnock in East Ayrshire. Reserves exist to continue until 2022.
[normal]By
[normal] the end of August 2013 site ha
[normal]d
[normal] produced 5,492,00
[normal]0 tonnes of coal 
[normal]supplying English
[normal] power stations by rail and contributing to an indigenous solution to UK energy security.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Greenburn operation currently employs 151 hourly paid individuals and additionally 48 sub-contractors are permanently employed 
[normal]giving a total of 199. Of this total 84 live within 10 miles of the site and 116 live within a 15 mile radius. 
[normal]It is estimated that 160 indirect jobs and 234 induced jobs (jobs supported by
[normal] employee spending) are employed
[normal]. 
[normal]These figure are in the context o
[normal]f significant unemployment of 10.9% (April 2012 to March 2013)
[normal] 
[normal]for East Ayrshire
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Kier have also contributed £1.54 million (end August 2013) into the local community trust which provides funding to local community projects and will continue to contribut
[normal]e on future production.  Kier Group plc has established a Non-Vocational Qualification (NVQ) Centre at Greenburn. To date the Centre has completed 116 vocational qualifications in level 2 Plant Operations plus 6 supervisors achieving level 3 awards.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case Study 3: 
[normal]Sibelco Kingsteignton (Bovey Basin, Devon) Ball Clay Operations
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Devon Ball Clay operations provide a range of plastic clays unique in Europe and much of the rest of the world. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The properties of these premium Ball Clays and the consiste
[normal]ncy of the blended products are very highly regarded globally, with exports to over 80 countries and the fact that more than 50% of the world’s sanitary
[normal] 
[normal]ware contains UK Ball Clay as an essential ingredient. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are few if any viable alternatives to the
[normal] UK Ball Clay component in the UK and the EU sanitary ceramics industry. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sanitary
[normal] 
[normal]ware producers regard the UK Ball Clays as essential to their production process. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Similarly there are currently no viable substitute materials for Ball Clay in most other c
[normal]eramic applications. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UK Ball Clay is of great importance with potentially in the order of 70-80,000 jobs at risk if the supply of ball clay is interrupted. (Source: DTI). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Typically ceramic manufacturers cannot carry large stocks of Ball Clay and th
[normal]us are highly dependent on the producers for frequent and uninterrupted deliveries.
[normal] 
[normal]The recently published National Planning Policy Framework reaffirmed the status of Ball Clay as a nationally important mineral in the context of the English planning syste
[normal]m. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]This status is nothing new and has been consistently afforded to Ball Clay in the UK since the Government’s Standing Conference in the 1940s, in part, due to its scarcity and limited distribution in the global context.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sibelco’s operations 
[normal]contribute some £15m to the local economy of Newton Abbot and sustain direct employment of over 200 people in the local area, together with a significant number of indirect jobs from servicing through to catering. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The international trade in Ball Clay is a
[normal]lso an integral element in sustaining Devon’s local ports, particularly Teignmouth, with between 80 and 90% of extracted mineral being exported. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The export of Ball Clay through Teignmouth consistently equates to circa 60% of the total annual tonnage throu
[normal]gh the docks, being almost twice the volume of the next highest tonnage (animal feed). (Source: Teignmouth Harbour Commissioners Financial Report: Y/E April 2011).
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The £10m realignment of the B3193 Chudleigh Road currently being developed, will release 
[normal]approximately 3,500,000 tonnes (3.5mt) of consented premium grade plastic clays with an estimated 81% yield (average yield of Bovey Basin Ball Clays is circa 65%), over the next 22 years. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, the 3.5mt is only the first phase of development, with the
[normal] existing B3193 currently sterilising an estimated total of 24mt of premium grade Ball Clay.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.10
[normal]              
[normal]Globally
[normal], the London Stock Exchange Group (LSEG) advise that
[normal] listed 
[normal] extractive industry companies account for approximately 16 per cent of LSEG’s markets b
[normal]y number of companies and 22 per cent by market capitalisation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.11
[normal]              
[normal]The development of the UK as a listing destination for extractive industry companies benefits the UK economy in many ways, including job creation, taxation, and strengthening the market
[normal] – for example by increasing the diversity of the UK’s capital markets - which benefits other listed companies and the wider financial services sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.12
[normal]              
[normal]By forming part of a global extractive industries peer group, these companies attract specialised 
[normal]global investors, analysts and intermediaries to London, giving them access to a global pool of investment capital. The UK’s financial services sector also benefits from extractive industry companies choosing to list in London. Regardless of where a compan
[normal]y is incorporated, it is likely to employ UK banks, legal firms and communications firms in its syndicate as it undertakes its IPO (initial public offering) process and whilst it is listed on the market. This provides a source of revenue and job creation f
[normal]or the UK’s financial services sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.13
[normal]              
[normal]Another way the listed and quoted extractive industry companie
[normal]s
[normal] support the growth of the UK economy is though taxation. There are 196 UK-incorporated extractive industry companies on our markets. The LSEG estim
[normal]ates from these figures 
[normal]that extractive companies on their
[normal] markets, as a group, 
[normal]pay £23 billion in domestic taxes
[normal] – more than Government spending on transport or housing and environment for 2013/14
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.14
[normal]              
[normal]The contribution of UK listed global mining industry to the UK economy is 
[normal]also 
[normal]well documented in the recent UKTI publication UK – Deliveri
[normal]ng Global Mining Solution. This 
[normal]states: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UK has world leading expertise in all aspects of the mining lifecycle. 
[normal]This publication showcases a wide selection of capabilities and case studies from UK organisations, institutions, consultants, companies and experts. It demonstrates that UK companies have the depth, breadth and global reach to deliver expert, effective an
[normal]d profitable solutions throughout
[normal] the mining lifecycle and beyond.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://www.ukti.gov.uk/uktihome/search.ht
[normal]ml?sort=ByScore&amp;search=UK+delivering+global+mining+solutions&amp;sector=-1&amp;country=-1&amp;focusOn=-1
